#########################################################################################################
####    READ THIS FIRST #################################################################################
#########################################################################################################

**************************************************************************************************
*** IMPORTANT: for the current v7.6.8 Setonix setup, run make_gist_config_try.py.              ***
*** Do NOT use make_gist_config.py as the default generator for this repository.                ***
*** make_gist_config.py is kept only as the older/reference version.                            ***
**************************************************************************************************

These instructions are intended to simplify and homogenize the set-up of GIST configuration files
used as input to run GIST and create MAUVE data products.

You do need:

-- A MAUVE GIST master configuration file: i.e. MAUVE_MasterConfig_v7.6.8_setonix.yaml
   This file includes all the important settings for the GIST MAUVE runs. 
   The file name includes the version of GIST on which is based and the SN to which cubes are binned.


-- The MAUVE GIST set-up file including ID, z, EB-V and velocity dispersion of all MAUVE targets
   These are used to create the .yaml file as they are needed to currently run GIST


 **************************************************************************************************
 *** You should not edit this file without authorization by the data prodcuts working group ***  
 *** Any changes should also be reported to the CHANGE_LOG file AND to the #gist-setup Slack channel
 ***
 *** If you need to change the file, please copy the current file (before changes) to the "old" folder
 *** Ideally add a sub-fix with the date in which the file has been changed.  
 *************************************************************************************************** 


#############################################################################################################
#
# HOW TO CREATE A .YAML GIST CONFIGURATION FILE ############################################################
#
#############################################################################################################

First, make sure you know:

-- How many CPUs you want to use
-- The coordinates (in pixels) of the centre of the cube, if you want to override the CSV value
-- Check that the name of the master_config, mauve_info_file, cube_centers_file and cube_sub listed in the "make_gist_config_try" file are correct. 


Then, you can run 

>>> python make_gist_config_try.py  GALAXYID

e.g., python make_gist_config_try.py IC3392

By default, make_gist_config_try.py uses:

-- -cpu 128
-- the galaxy centre from cube_centers_v3tk.csv

Special case:

-- NGC4567_8 is a combined cube. The cube centre table contains NGC4567_8, but
   the MAUVE setup FITS table contains separate rows for NGC4567 and NGC4568.
   make_gist_config_try.py keeps NGC4567_8 as RUN_ID/INPUT/MASK and uses the
   mean z, EB-V and sigma from the NGC4567 and NGC4568 setup-table rows.

If you need to override the CPU count or centre manually, run:

>>> python make_gist_config_try.py  GALAXYID  -cpu NN -center NN,NN

e.g., python make_gist_config_try.py IC3392 -cpu 128 -center 219,219

This will create a .yaml file (e.g., IC3392_MAUVE_MasterConfig_v7.6.8_setonix.yaml) ready for you to use. 

############################################################################################################
# LAST CHECKS
############################################################################################################
Before running GIST, make sure that:

- you copy the .yaml file created in a suitable folder. Please do not leave it in the folder where this README is located

- make sure that your "configFiles" folder is up-to-date (in case of recent GIST updates) and the "defaultDir" file is in order

- make sure you that you have all the relevant stellar population models in the "spectralTemplates" folder

##############################################################################################################  
# You are good to go!
#
# HAVE FUN!!!!!
##############################################################################################################



